"Vermeer M., Rahmstorf S.","Global sea level linked to global temperature",2009,"Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America","106","51",,"21527","21532",,,10.1073/pnas.0907765106,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-76049103123&partnerID=40&md5=51819a572c26328f5d1cefcf3506ef3d","Department of Surveying, Helsinki University of Technology, P.O. Box 1200, FI-02150, Espoo, Finland; Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research, Telegrafenberg A62, 14473 Potsdam, Germany","Vermeer, M., Department of Surveying, Helsinki University of Technology, P.O. Box 1200, FI-02150, Espoo, Finland; Rahmstorf, S., Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research, Telegrafenberg A62, 14473 Potsdam, Germany","We propose a simple relationship linking global sea-level variations on time scales of decades to centuries to global mean temperature. This relationship is tested on synthetic data from a global climate model for the past millennium and the next century. When applied to observed data of sea level and temperature for 1880-2000, and taking into account known anthropogenic hydrologic contributions to sea level, the correlation is >0.99, explaining 98% of the variance. For future global temperature scenarios of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change's Fourth Assessment Report, the relationship projects a sea-level rise ranging from 75 to 190 cm for the period 1990-2100.","Climate; Global warming; Ocean; Projections","article; climate change; environmental temperature; greenhouse effect; hydrology; priority journal; sea level",,,,,,"Rahmstorf, S., Recent climate observations compared to projections (2007) Science, 316, p. 709; (2007) The Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, , Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change , eds Solomon S, et al, Cambridge Univ Press, Cambridge UK; Rahmstorf, S., A semiempirical approach to projecting future sea-level rise (2007) Science, 315, pp. 368-370; Horton, R., Sea-level rise projections for current generation CGCMs based on the semiempirical method (2008) Geophys Res Lett, 35, pp. L02715; Edwards, R., Sea levels: Resolution and uncertainty (2007) Progr Phys Geogr, 31, pp. 621-632; von Storch, H., Zorita, E., Gonzalez-Rouco, J.F., Relationship between global mean sea level and global mean temperature in a climate simulation of the past millennium (2008) Ocean Dyn, 58, pp. 227-236; Oppenheimer, M., O'Neill, B.C., Webster, M., Negative learning (2008) Clim Change, 89, pp. 155-172; Grinsted, A., Moore, J.C., Jefrejeva, S., Reconstructing sea level from paleo and projected temperatures 200 to 2100 AD (2009) Clim Dyn, , 10.1007/s00382-008-0507-2; Oerlemans, J., Modeling the response of glaciers to climate warming (1998) Clim Dyn, 14, pp. 267-274; Holgate, S., Jevrejeva, S., Woodworth, P., Brewer, S., Comment on a semiempirical approach to projecting future sea-level rise (1866) Science, 317; Schmith, T., Johansen, S., Thejll, P., Comment on a semiempirical approach to projecting future sea-level rise (1866) Science, 317; Rahmstorf, S., Response to comments on a semiempirical approach to projecting future sea-level rise (1866) Science, 317; Montoya, M., The Earth system model of intermediate complexity CLIMBER-3α. Part I: Description and performance for present-day conditions (2005) Clim Dyn, 26, pp. 237-263; Goosse, H., Renssen, H., Timmermann, A., Bradley, R.S., Internal and forced climate variability during the last millennium: A model-data comparison using ensemble simulations (2005) Q Sci Rev, 24, pp. 1345-1360; Ramillien, G., Land water storage contribution to sea level from GRACE geoid data over 2003-2006 (2008) Global Planetary Change, 60, pp. 381-392; Cazenave, A., Sea-level budget over 2003-2008:Areevaluation from GRACE space gravimetry, satellite altimetry, and Argo (2008) Global Planetary Change, 65, pp. 83-88; Hansen, J., A closer look at United States and global surface temperature change (2001) J Geophys Res, 10